[Student "S"]
{When responding to a takeout double use these guidelines:0-8 points: bid a suit cheaply9-11 points: bid a suit with a jump12 or more points: cue-bid the opponent's suit

With 13 points you cue-bid 2\D. Partner says 2\H.

You are forced to game, now you must find a suit. Partner suggested \Hs, you suggest \Ss. Partner agrees \Ss and bids the game.

East plays 4\S. South leads \DA, \DK, \DQ. North plays \D8 then \D2.

<b>East plays 4\S. South leads \DA, \DK, \DQ. North plays \D8 then \D2.</b>

Losers: \S 0 : \H 0 : \D 3 : \C 1 : Total = 4

If you could ruff that \D then one of your \D losers would be eliminated - if North didn't over-ruff. But you know that North is going to over-ruff. So don't ruff it, discard dummy's \C6 instead. Later you can ruff your \C loser in dummy.

If you had ruffed, North would have over-ruffed. And you would still have a \C loser. You don't have to worry about a fourth \D lead because you can ruff in your hand higher than any card North might ruff with.}
[Play "W"]DA

