[Student "S"]
{You open 1\S. North overcalls 2\H and partner bids 4\S.

West plays 4\S. North leads \HA, \HK, \HQ.

<b>West plays 4\S. North leads \HA, \HK, \HQ.</b>

Losers: \S 1 : \H 2 : \D 1 : \C 0 : Total = 4

You have already lost the 2 \Hs and you will definitely lose the \D. So you cannot lose a \S as well. When you have 11 cards in a suit missing the King, the recommended play is to play for the drop. But the recommended play shouldn't be used on this hand because you know that South has the \SK. How do you know this? Because North has turned up with 10 points in \Hs, (the A K Q and a fifth one). If he held the \SK as well he would have had 13 points and a good suit and would have opened he bidding. But he didn't open, so he doesn't have the \SK.

Ruff the \H. Play the \D8 to dummy's \D10. If South takes the \DA win his return and enter dummy with the \DQ. When in dummy lead the \SQ and finesse South out of his \SK.

You have to listen to the bidding and draw conclusions from what is bid - and not bid. Because he passed originally you could figure out that North could not hold the \SK. Or, if you had needed to know, he could also not have had the \DA.}
[Play "W"]HA

